observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Instruct the Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;

Enjoin the GSO-Designate to maintain Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELC and be reconciled with the PCs of the GSO-Designate;

Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect a more reliable balances of PPE accounts.

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct:

The Municipal Accountant, GSO and Municipal Assessor to coordinate and reconcile their records;

The GSO to complete its files and records of the Certificate of titles and other proof of ownership;

The Municipal Assessor and Municipal Accountant to ensure the proper valuation of the Land account for a fairly presented financial statements; and 

The GSO and Municipal Assessor to facilitate and process the titling of land owned by the City Government to establish legal ownership and safeguard the Municipality from third party claims

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
Create a monitoring report on these payables indicating the status, terms and conditions of the agreement, date of grant, aging of payables, and other relevant details pertaining to the utilization, liquidation, and remittance for a more efficient and effective monitoring;
Coordinate with the concerned source agency to (a) Secure a copy of the MOAs or any documents from the concerned agencies, if no copies are available within the concerned officers-in-charge, to support the payables as well as details such as terms and conditions of the grant to identify the nature of such payables and (b) furnish a copy of the said agreement to the Audit Team;
Disclose additional details of the Due to NGAs account, such as, but not limited to: (a) name of source agencies; (b) purpose of the funds; (c) date of grant; (d) implementation status under Note 8 of the Notes to Financial Statements;
Prioritize the completion of the necessary documents for liquidation and remittance of the remaining balance of funds to DA-RFO I and ensure the timely submission of liquidation reports for all fund transfers from other government agencies, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 94-013;
Coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer and the MPDC on the projects implemented or to be implemented relating to the long outstanding payables under Due to NGAs by reviewing the MOAs and any related documents as to the terms and conditions of the grant;
Transfer the balance of LGU’s share from PCSO under Trust Fund to the General Fund and prepare the adjusting journal entry for the total receipt of LGU’s Share from tobacco excise tax and the Share from PCSO using the proforma entry below:
Adjusting entry under General Fund if the books of the Municipal Government is not yet closed and receipts pertain to current year:
Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to remit the collection of the share of DPWH on the building permits and other related fees to the recipients specified under the procedural guidelines provided in DPWH-DILG JMC No. 001 dated July 4, 2015.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to:
Observe the timely remittance and recording of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee, as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth in order to avoid possible penalties;
Coordinate with Philhealth and formally submit all available proof of payment pertaining to the noted deficiencies in the SPA regarding the unpaid balances for November 2015. This will help ensure that the paid amount is properly reflected in their records, eliminate the continued appearance of the unpaid balance in future SPAs, and avoid the risk of incurring further penalties or interest charges.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following:

a) The OIC-GSO and Accounting Office maintain complete an accurate PPELC for each category of PPE pursuant to Section 114 on the Manual on NGAS for LGUs in order to promote effective monitoring and controls over PPE;

b) A reconciliation of the OIC-GSO and Accounting records be done after the conduct of physical count;

c) The Inventory Committee submit the Physical Inventory Reports to the Property Officer and COA Office for verification and reconciliation of the result of the physical inventory with the complete Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and the Property Cards maintained by the Property and Accounting Office; and

d) The OIC-GSO and Accounting Office comply with the prescribed procedures in COA Circular No. 89-296 on the disposal of unserviceable PPE, if any.

We have recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the:

a. Bids and Award Committee to submit the Purchase Order/Contract Agreement with all the complete bidding document within five (5) working days upon perfection as provided in the COA Circular No. 2009-001, and; 

b. Accounting Office to ensure that all the necessary documents as required under COA Circular 2012-001 are attached for the completeness and legality of all claims and payment of procurement.

